    \"text\": \"“Understanding LoRA as Knowledge Memory”\\nRight now, most research treats LoRA like a cheap fine-tune toggle, but if you want to use it as swappable knowledge memory, the rule of thumb has been mostly vibes.\\nThis paper fixes that with a systematic audit of LoRA-as-memory, where it maps how storage scales and saturates with rank.\\nIt shows you get way more memory per token by training on QA/summaries instead of raw passages.\"
