    \"url\": \"https://x.com/MoodiSadi/status/2029117740385222798\",
    \"text\": \"Great paper! The key insight: QA/summary training gives 3-5x more memory per token than raw passages. For practical LoRA-as-memory: 1) Train on distilled QA pairs not raw docs 2) Keep rank ≤8 for saturation point 3) Use cross-attention for retrieval. This beats the 'vibes' approach.\"
  },
  {
    \"url\": \"https://x.com/ysu_ChatData/status/2029488094693761355\",
    \"text\": \"Really nice framing. Treating LoRA as a swappable memory module makes the tradeoffs feel much clearer. The point about QA or summaries packing more memory per token matches what we see in practice. Curious if the paper gives a practical heuristic for picking rank given a target knowledge size and acceptable interference.\"
